No. The CLT requires finite variance (and finite mean), and the Cauchy distribution has neither. The "σ" in your formula doesn't exist — the population variance is infinite, and the sample standard deviation does not converge to any finite value as n grows. Worse, the sample mean of n iid Cauchy(0, γ) variables is itself Cauchy(0, γ), with exactly the same scale as a single observation. So averaging 1,000 samples gives you no improvement in precision over averaging 1, and the sampling distribution is not even approximately normal. The ±1.96·s/√n interval will have coverage far below 95%, and its width is essentially meaningless (driven by whatever extreme values happened to land in your sample). For Cauchy data, use the sample median (which is asymptotically normal with scale πγ/(2√n)) or estimate the location parameter γ via MLE, and build intervals from those.
